This model was adopted on the basis of the ecological assumption that the response function (reaction norm) of populations to any change of climate follows a quadratic, symmetric “bell-shaped” function with a maximum at, or near a transfer distance of 0, i.e., close to the climate of the provenance, assuming local adaptation (
 Wang, O’Neill & Aitken, 2010; 
 Kapeller et al., 2012; 
 Leites et al., 2012a; 
 Leites et al., 2012b; 
 Yang et al., 2015; 
 Sáenz-Romero et al., 2017). The response to climatic transfer includes a quadratic function (
 D
 2 term), but the term for climate at seed source (
 C term) is based on a linear function. A large body of experimental results from common gardens of forest trees is available, indicating a linear, clinal variation of populations along climatic or geographic gradients (
 Mátyás & Yeatman, 1992; 
 Alberto et al., 2013; for a review: 
 Morgenstern, 1996).
